{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489445","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489445"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:17:18+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:17:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"663"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"663","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/663"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.24,0.03,0.05,0.66,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"663"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114601"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"663","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/663"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"663"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96604"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1165"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"5899"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3203"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13829"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33632"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39375"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114601","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114601"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 70-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a 24-hour history of severe right subcostal pain radiating to her back. The pain is constant and unrelieved by a hot pack applied earlier today. She has no significant medical history except hypercholesterolaemia. She takes atorvastatin. She does not smoke and drinks alcohol occasionally.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears uncomfortable. Her pulse rate is 100/min, blood pressure 130/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. Abdominal examination reveals a soft abdomen with no tenderness or masses. Four hours after presentation, examination reveals the following (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Erythema ab igne","Biliary colic","Acute cholecystitis","Herpes zoster","Rectus sheath haematoma"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with severe unilateral pain followed by the development of vesicular lesions in a dermatomal distribution, characteristic of herpes zoster (shingles). The prodromal pain of herpes zoster typically precedes the rash by 48-72 hours, though this can range from one to five days. This temporal sequence often leads to misdiagnosis, as patients present with severe pain before any visible skin changes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHerpes zoster\u003C/strong\u003E results from reactivation of varicella-zoster virus dormant in dorsal root ganglia. The T10 dermatome involvement explains the right subcostal pain radiating to the back. The characteristic grouped vesicles on an erythematous base appearing in a dermatomal distribution confirm the diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute cholecystitis\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with right upper quadrant pain, fever, and localised tenderness under the right costal margin. Patients usually have associated nausea and vomiting. The absence of abdominal tenderness and the subsequent appearance of dermatomal vesicles make this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBiliary colic\u003C/strong\u003E presents as episodic right upper quadrant or epigastric pain, often precipitated by fatty meals. The pain typically lasts minutes to hours rather than being constant over 24 hours. The dermatomal rash excludes this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EErythema ab igne\u003C/strong\u003E presents as a reticulated, erythematous, hyperpigmented skin lesion caused by chronic heat exposure. A single application of a hot pack would not cause this condition, and it does not present with vesicular lesions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERectus sheath haematoma\u003C/strong\u003E presents with abdominal pain and a palpable mass along the rectus muscle, often following trauma or anticoagulation. The dermatomal distribution of vesicles is not consistent with this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Herpes zoster pain typically precedes the characteristic vesicular rash by 24-72 hours, leading to potential misdiagnosis.","Dermatomal distribution of pain should raise suspicion for herpes zoster even in the absence of rash.","Abdominal pain can be a presentation of non-abdominal pathology including herpes zoster affecting thoracic dermatomes."],"references":["Saguil A, Kane S, Mercado M, Lauters R. Herpes Zoster and Postherpetic Neuralgia: Prevention and Management. Am Fam Physician. 2017 Nov 15;96(10):656-663."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96604"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"663"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"15623"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"15623","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/15623"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/e033355e-b290-4c1f-968f-17e8f4e1624c.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/e033355e-b290-4c1f-968f-17e8f4e1624c.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions"